{"id":"1509.08236","submitter":"Mats Granath","authors":"Mats Granath and Alvaro Perez-Diaz","title":"Diffusion and localization of relative strategy scores in the Minority\n  Game","comments":null,"journal-ref":"J Stat Phys (2016)","doi":"10.1007/s10955-016-1607-8","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.dis-nn nlin.AO physics.soc-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the equilibrium distribution of relative strategy scores of agents\nin the asymmetric phase ($\\alpha\\equiv P/N\\gtrsim 1$) of the basic Minority\nGame using sign-payoff, with $N$ agents holding two strategies over $P$\nhistories. We formulate a statistical model that makes use of the gauge freedom\nwith respect to the ordering of an agent's strategies to quantify the\ncorrelation between the attendance and the distribution of strategies. The\nrelative score $x\\in\\mathbb{Z}$ of the two strategies of an agent is described\nin terms of a one dimensional random walk with asymmetric jump probabilities,\nleading either to a static and asymmetric exponential distribution centered at\n$x=0$ for fickle agents or to diffusion with a positive or negative drift for\nfrozen agents. In terms of scaled coordinates $x/\\sqrt{N}$ and $t/N$ the\ndistributions are uniquely given by $\\alpha$ and in quantitative agreement with\ndirect simulations of the game. As the model avoids the reformulation in terms\nof a constrained minimization problem it can be used for arbitrary payoff\nfunctions with little calculational effort and provides a transparent and\nsimple formulation of the dynamics of the basic Minority Game in the asymmetric\nphase.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Sep 2015 08:51:52 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 27 Aug 2016 14:01:29 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-08-31"}
{"id":"1509.08237","submitter":"Jinsong Zhao","authors":"J. S. Zhao, Y. M. Voitenko, D. J. Wu, and M. Y. Yu","title":"Kinetic Alfv\\'{e}n turbulence below and above ion-cyclotron frequency","comments":"9 Pages, 3 Figures, and 2 Tables","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1002/2015JA021959","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP astro-ph.SR physics.space-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Alfv\\'{e}nic turbulent cascade perpendicular and parallel to the background\nmagnetic field is studied accounting for anisotropic dispersive effects and\nturbulent intermittency. The perpendicular dispersion and intermittency make\nthe perpendicular-wavenumber magnetic spectra steeper and speed up production\nof high ion-cyclotron frequencies by the turbulent cascade. On the contrary,\nthe parallel dispersion makes the spectra flatter and decelerate the frequency\ncascade above the ion-cyclotron frequency. Competition of the above factors\nresults in spectral indices distributed in the interval [-2,-3], where -2 is\nthe index of high-frequency space-filling turbulence, and -3 is the index of\nlow-frequency intermittent turbulence formed by tube-like fluctuations. Spectra\nof fully intermittent turbulence fill a narrower range of spectral indices\n[-7/3,-3], which almost coincides with the range of indexes measured in the\nsolar wind. This suggests that the kinetic-scale turbulent spectra are shaped\nmainly by dispersion and intermittency. A small mismatch with measured indexes\nof about 0.1 can be associated with damping effects not studied here.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 28 Sep 2015 08:58:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-23"}
